# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chuuk-state
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] An independence referendum for Chuuk State to secede from the Federated States of Micronesia was originally scheduled to take place in March 2015.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] However, it has been delayed three times and it is uncertain if it will take place.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The most populous of the four states within the FSM, Chuuk has high levels of unemployment and there are long-standing tensions over the distribution of funding within the FSM.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Other concerns include political power within the federation and the preservation of cultural identity.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In 2012, the Chuuk State Government created the Chuuk Political Status Commission (CPSC) to study potential future statuses for Chuuk.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In 2014, the CPSC recommended independence with a separate Compact of Free Association (CFA) with the United States.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In 2015, the governor of Chuuk postponed the initial referendum citing the need for greater citizen awareness and a lack of preparedness.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The Chuuk State Legislature delayed the second planned referendum in 2019 for a year and also suspended the CPSC.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The third delay in February 2020 pushed the referendum back two years to 2022, and the referendum did not take place that year.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The CPSC has actively campaigned for independence, holding public hearings both in Chuuk and in areas with significant overseas Chuukese populations.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Opposition has come from both civilians and the FSM Government.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The potential timing of the referendum is significant, as parts of the current CFA agreement expired in 2023.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The United States has stated that a similar agreement would not be offered to an independent Chuuk.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Islands within Micronesia came under the jurisdiction of the United States in 1947, as the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] This territory was divided into six administrative districts: Chuuk, the Marshall Islands, the Northern Mariana Islands, Palau, Pohnpei, and Yap State (Yap).
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Kosrae was later separated from Pohnpei.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Discussions on self-government included an extensive debate over the power of a potential central government compared to the island groups.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] While the United States wished for the islands to remain united, local political pressure led to the Northern Mariana Islands being separated from the others in the 1970s.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Pressure from the Marshall Islands and Palau led the United States to agree that each island group could select its own negotiators; both island groups rejected the Federated States of Micronesia's proposed constitution during a 12 July 1978 referendum.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The remaining four island groups became the Federated States of Micronesia (FSM).
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] This federation signed the Compact of Free Association (CFA) with the United States in 1982.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] This compact creates an alliance between the FSM and the United States, with the United States military able to enter the territory of the FSM.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Under the compact, the United States agreed to provide financial grants to FSM and extend free movement into the United States to FSM citizens.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The United States negotiated similar agreements with the now separate Marshall Islands and Palau.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The FSM was recognized as an independent state in 1986.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Renegotiations between the two countries over the CFA concluded in 2003, extending the deal to 2023.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] On May 23, 2023, the FSM and the United States entered into another 20-year compact which includes $3.3 billion in funding over the life of the agreement.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The FSM is a loose federation, and ideas relating to the secession of its states have existed since its creation.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] During the 2003 CFA negotiations, there were rumors that each state would negotiate separate compacts, although this did not happen.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] State identities are strong, with the central government often seen as distant, and those from other states sometimes considered foreigners.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] However, Chuuk is the only state in which the executive and legislative branches of government have officially taken up secession.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] State officials lead the Chuuk Independence Movement.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Among Chuukese and within the Chuuk Government, concerns exist about the distribution of funds among the FSM states.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] While Chuuk is the most populous state, accounting for almost half of the country's population, it receives only 30% of the financial grants under the CFA.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In 2000, its unemployment rate stood at 34.2%, the highest in the country and over 12 percentage points more than the national average.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Furthermore, the national government does not share revenue from commercial fishing with the states.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Independence is also seen as a way to strengthen Chuukese identity and safeguard Chuukese culture.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Independence advocates claim that an independent Chuuk would bring increased economic opportunity, including through control over its exclusive economic zone, generating up to $40 million per year.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] A new taxation system and the full retention of their taxes would generate further funds.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] They also claim an independent Chuuk would be able to claim some funds from existing Micronesian funds.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] They also claim a revised CFA would better suit Chuuk.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Independence advocates saw the Compact renegotiation leading up to the 2023 expiration as an opportunity for Chuuk to negotiate with the United States on its own terms.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Chuuk State Attorney General Sabino Asor has said the movement seeks to replicate the CFA for an independent Chuuk.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] This idea was explicitly rejected by the United States, with its ambassador to FSM engaging in a media campaign to make it clear such an option would not be available.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The legal mechanism by which Chuuk could obtain independence is unclear.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] One proposal is to ask the other states to amend the FSM constitution following a successful vote.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Some independence advocates believe the constitution has no provision to prevent secession.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] However, others note the constitution obliges all states "to promote the principles of unity".
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Changing the constitution requires 75% approval, along with the votes of 75% of the states.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Even after a successful vote for independence, Chuuk would remain part of FSM for perhaps years as it negotiates its independence.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The CPSC claims that Chuuk has the right to declare independence under international law, following the Kosovo precedent.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] They have also claimed independence is also justified under the United Nations Declaration of Human Rights Article 15.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The Chuuk State Government established the Chuuk Political Status Commission (CPSC) in 2012 through Chuuk State Public Law 11-18 (CSL 11-12-08).
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] This commission had 12 voting members, 10 selected by the five regional groups present in the legislature and two by the governor.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The State Senate President and the Speaker of the House of Representatives participated in the CPSC as non-voting members.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The new commission was tasked with determining the best future status for Chuuk in light of the upcoming expiry of the CFA.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Under CSL 11-12-18, the CPSC was meant to conduct a public education program in the 18 months following its inception in January 2013 and then submit its final report.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In February 2014, the Chuuk State Government extended its mandate for public hearings by seven months.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Comparing several options, this report recommended independence with a renegotiated CFA for the future of Chuuk.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The report declared other options were "impractical, unrealistic or impossible".
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The CPSC claimed feedback obtained during meetings and internal discussions were the basis of its report.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] This, despite few meetings being held, with most of them taking place among overseas communities.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The Chuuk State Legislature accepted the report on 19 December 2014 during a joint session, months before the expiration of the public hearing mandate.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Planning then began for a referendum on independence.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The timetable provided in the report was an independence referendum in March 2015, after which if independence is voted for a new constitution would be drawn up by October 2015.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The new constitution would be put to a referendum in March 2017, after which an election would produce a new government that could declare independence.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The referendum was scheduled for 3 March 2015, to coincide with parliamentary elections.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Mori stated that individuals within the CPSC were the same as some involved in previous attempts to separate Faichuk from the rest of Chuuk into its own state.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Videlino Raatior, a former Chuuk resident now living in Hawaii, formed the Chuuk Reform Movement to advocate for continued federation.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Public hearings in late 2014 and early 2015 in response to this report elicited opposition from communities both within and outside of Chuuk.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Concerns were raised over the short timeframe between the report's submission and the proposed referendum date.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The US Ambassador to the FSM rejected claims by one member of the CPSC that they had discussed the issue with the United States in January 2015.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] On 27 January 2015, the legal counsel of the FSM embassy to the United States submitted a memorandum to Mori disputing many claims made in the CPSC's report.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] On the same date, Mori approved the creation of a task force to campaign against Chuukese independence.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] This task force included members of the cabinet and other national government officials.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] It began its own campaign through public hearings within the FSM and abroad.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In February 2015 the FSM Department of Justice issued a similar memorandum, claiming the constitution prohibited secession.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In late February 2015, Chuuk Governor Johnson Elimo postponed the vote indefinitely through an executive order.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The Public Affairs Office released a statement saying that more consultation and awareness was needed.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The simultaneous elections were also postponed, because of election material not being ready.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Also cited as reasons to delay the referendum were shortcomings in the work of the CPSC, and concerns over the feasibility of holding the referendum simultaneously with the federal elections.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Elimo then asked the legislature to determine a new date for the referendum.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In response to the postponement, Mori suspended the anti-independence task force, and called for tripartite talks between the FSM, Chuuk, and the United States, to address the concerns underlying the independence campaign.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] On 19 November 2015, representatives of Chuuk within the Congress of the Federated States of Micronesia sponsored a resolution to end the CFA.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Sabino Asor remained chair of the CPSC during this new period.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The CPSC continued to hold meetings to provide information on independence throughout Chuuk, and in areas with other significant Chuukese populations, such as Guam and Hawaii.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] They claimed over 50% of the population supported independence.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] During this period, former FSM president John Haglelgam warned against independence.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In 2018, the United States Ambassador to the FSM, Robert Riley, said that independence would mean an end to the CFA agreement, and that the United States would not negotiate a similar agreement with an independent Chuuk.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] As of 2018, there were around 45,000 eligible Chuukese voters.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] While the referendum was scheduled to coincide with the 2019 parliamentary elections, the CSPC and Elimo attempted to move the referendum forward to January 2019, eliciting concern among overseas voters.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] This proposal was suspended initially until 27 August 2018.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] One candidate for the FSM congress from Northwest Chuuk expressed a desire for the outer island regions in Chuuk to be able to separate from Chuuk to stay in the FSM in the event Chuuk as a whole voted for independence, either as a rump Chuuk state or by integrating into neighboring states.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In a special session of the FSM Congress, one Chuuk senator introduced a resolution requesting a reconsideration of the independence referendum; however, it did not reach the floor.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] CSL 14-23, which served to postpone the 5 March 2019 referendum to March 2020, was passed in October 2018 by the Chuuk State Legislature.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] After it was subsequently vetoed by acting Governor Marius Akapito, it was passed again on 6 December 2019 by both houses of the legislature, overriding the veto.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] CSL 14-23 also "suspended CSPC from further carrying out its public education function on the state's Independence Movement".
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Following the 2019 postponement, the CSPC stated it would sue the state legislature in response, citing violations of free speech.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] On 22 February 2019, state officials announced that the referendum had once again been postponed until an undetermined date.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The Chuuk State Legislature's chief legal counsel stated that more time was needed to understand potential constitutional implications, while the FSM Government stated that secession as proposed in the referendum was illegal and would require constitutional amendments.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The FSM Government also noted that the time could be used for further public education on the matter.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] By 5 March, when the referendum was meant to take place, the new timeframe of March 2020 had already been decided.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In February 2020 the vote was postponed for a third time, being rescheduled for 2022.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Asor stated that this was to allow the FSM time to "correct some of the deficiencies".
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Mori believed that the independence referendum would not happen in 2022 either, noting there were still unanswered questions surrounding the referendum despite the multiple attempts at organizing one.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] By January 2022, the CPSC no longer had any staff or offices.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] While the referendum has not been officially abandoned, no relevant bill had passed in the FSM Senate, and it is not on the immediate political agenda.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Northwest Chuuk Senator Matt Kuor has suggested that it may become relevant in 2023, when the Compact of Free Association is expected to be adjusted following negotiations.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Given Chuuk's closeness to Guam, it is considered a strategically important location.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] The United States has warned Chuuk against independence, amid concern China's influence may increase in an independent Chuuk.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] In addition to its strategic location, Chuuk contains one of the deepest lagoons in the Pacific.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] China has already paid $50 million towards building roads in Chuuk, and funded the construction of the Chuuk Government Complex.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Sabino Asor has explicitly rejected the idea of inviting a Chinese military presence on an independent Chuuk, although they would welcome economic and diplomatic ties.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Chuukese working in the United States are concerned about how independence would affect their legal right to work there.
[src:chuuk-state/2022-chuukese-independence-referendum] Some independence advocates claim Chuukese people may be able to retain FSM citizenship upon independence.
[src:chuuk-state/alexander-r-narruhn] Narruhn graduated from Xavier High School and received a Bachelor of Arts in Business Administration and Master of Arts in Management from National University in San Diego.
[src:chuuk-state/alexander-r-narruhn] In 2008, he became the Secretary of the FSM Petroleum Corporation.
[src:chuuk-state/alexander-r-narruhn] In March 2021, he won a gubernatorial election and was sworn in on 13 April.
[src:chuuk-state/alexander-r-narruhn] On 19 April, he met with President David Panuelo.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The **Allies**, or **Allied powers**, formally referred to as the **United Nations** from 1942, were an international military coalition formed during World War II (1939–1945) to oppose the Axis powers.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Its principal members were the "Big Four" — the United Kingdom, the Soviet Union, the United States, and China.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Membership in the Allies varied during the course of the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] When the conflict broke out on 1 September 1939, the Allied coalition consisted of the United Kingdom, France, and Poland, as well as their respective dependencies, such as British India.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] They were joined by the independent dominions of the British Commonwealth: Canada, Australia, New Zealand and South Africa.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Consequently, the initial alliance resembled that of the First World War.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] As Axis forces began invading northern Europe and the Balkans, the Allies added the Netherlands, Belgium, Norway, Greece, and Yugoslavia.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union, which initially had a non-aggression pact with Germany (which resulted in the Soviet invasion of Poland) joined the Allies after the German invasion of the Soviet Union in June 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States, while providing some material support to European Allies since September 1940, remained formally neutral until the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor in December 1941, after which it declared war and officially joined the Allies.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Republic of China had already been at war with Japan since 1937 after the Marco Polo Bridge incident, and formally joined the Allies in December 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The "Big Three"—the United Kingdom, the Soviet Union, and the United States—were the principal contributors of manpower, resources and strategy, each playing a key role in achieving victory.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Relations between the United Kingdom and the United States were especially close, with their bilateral Atlantic Charter forming the basis of their alliance.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] A series of conferences between Allied leaders, diplomats, and military officials gradually shaped the makeup of the alliance, the direction of the war, and ultimately the postwar international order.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Allies became a formalized group upon the Declaration by United Nations on 1 January 1942, which was signed by 26 countries around the world; these ranged from governments in exile from the Axis occupation to small states far removed from the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Declaration officially recognized the Big Three and China as the "Four Powers", acknowledging their central role in prosecuting the war; they were also referred to as the "trusteeship of the powerful", and later as the "Four Policemen" of the United Nations.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Many more countries joined through to the final days of the war, including colonies and former Axis states.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] After the war ended, the Allies, and the Declaration that bound them, would become the basis of the modern United Nations.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the First World War, the Treaty of Versailles (1919) established the League of Nations in an attempt to create a system of collective security and prevent war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The League's covenant obliged members to protect the political and territorial integrity of all members against aggression.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Four of the major allies of the First World War—the United Kingdom, France, Italy and Japan—became permanent members of the league's council.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The league, however, was weakened by the failure of the United States to join and by the cumbersome rules for enforcing sanctions for breaches of its security provisions.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] France attempted to further protect itself against possible future German attack with the Franco-Polish alliance (1921) and the Franco-Czechoslovak alliance (1924).
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Under the Locarno treaties (1925), France, Britain, Belgium, Germany and Italy also guaranteed the borders between Germany and France and Germany and Belgium as defined in the Treaty of Versailles.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The system of collective security was weakened when Japan withdrew from the League in February 1933, following the League's criticism of Japan's invasion of Manchuria in 1931.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] A further blow came when Nazi Germany withdrew from the League and the world disarmament conference in October 1933.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In May 1935, France signed a mutual defence agreement with the Soviet Union, which Germany saw as directed against it.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In October 1935, Italy invaded Abyssinia and the league responded with weak, short-lived sanctions.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Germany remilitarised the Rhineland in March 1936 in contravention of the Versailles and Locarno treaties but Britain, France and the League of Nations imposed no sanctions.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain, however, announced that it would aid France and Belgium if they were the victims of aggression, and France stated that it would assist Britain and Belgium in the same circumstances.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In July 1937, Japan began an undeclared war in China.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The league found Japan's actions illegal and invited its members to impose sanctions.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In November, Italy joined the German and Japanese Anti-Comintern pact, and in December it left the league.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In March 1938, Germany invaded and annexed Austria in contravention of the Versailles treaty.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] France and Britain issued formal protests but took no further action.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain declined a Soviet offer to form a defensive alliance against Germany and also declined a French request to provide a security guarantee to Czechoslovakia, which was subject to German threats over its alleged mistreatment of the German-speaking majority in its Sudetenland region.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Instead, Britain continued its policy of appeasing Germany by putting pressure on Czechoslovakia to negotiate a solution acceptable to Hitler.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] As the crisis deepened, Britain, France, Germany, and Italy signed the Munich Agreement on 30 September 1938, whereby the Sudetenland was ceded to Germany against the wishes of the Czechoslovak government, and the signatories guaranteed the territorial integrity of the rump Czechoslovak state.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Germany invaded Czechoslovakia on 15 March 1939 in violation of the Munich Agreement.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Subsequently, Germany increased pressure on Poland to agree to the transfer of Danzig (a free city under the Versailles treaty) and the Polish corridor to Germany.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 31 March, Britain and France announced that they would come to Poland's aid if it were attacked.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Italy invaded Albania on 7 April, and Britain and France responded by issuing security guarantees to Greece, Romania and Turkey.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In May, France and Poland agreed to preliminary political and military protocols for mutual defence.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain and France also began negotiations for a defence treaty with the Soviet Union but little progress was made.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 22 May, Germany and Italy signed a military alliance known as the Pact of Steel.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The governments of Germany and the Soviet Union signed a non-aggression pact on 23 August, which included a secret protocol for the partition of Poland.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Two days later, Britain signed a military alliance with Poland.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 1 September 1939, Germany invaded Poland, and on 3 September, Britain and France declared war on Germany.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union invaded Poland from the east on 17 September but remained officially neutral in the war between Germany and the western allies.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Italy, Japan and the United States were also formally neutral in the conflict, although Italy eventually declared war on Britain and France on 10 June 1940.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and Canada declared war on Germany in the two weeks following the British declaration.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] An Anglo-French Supreme War Council was established to coordinate military decisions and it first met on 12 September 1939.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] By 1 October, Warsaw had fallen and the Polish government had escaped into exile.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following a lull in fighting between Germany and the western allies, Germany began its invasion of western Europe in April 1940, quickly overrunning Denmark, Norway, the Low Countries, and France.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The governments of these occupied countries, except France, fled, establishing governments-in-exile in London which Britain recognized as allies.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain recognized Charles de Gaulle as leader of the Free-French forces in London, which opposed the collaborationist French Vichy government.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Free French, however, were not recognized as a government-in-exile until 1944.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Czechoslovakia, Yugoslavia and Greece also established governments-in-exile in 1941 following the German advances towards eastern Mediterranean.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The First Inter-Allied Meeting took place in London in early June 1941 between the United Kingdom, the four allied British Dominions, the eight governments in exile, and Free France.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The meeting culminated with the Declaration of St James's Palace, which committed the signatories to work together until victory was achieved and an enduring peace secured.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 22 June 1941, Hitler broke the non-aggression agreement with Stalin and Axis forces invaded the Soviet Union.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain formed an alliance with the Soviet Union in July, whereby they agreed to assist one another by any means, and to never negotiate a separate peace.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The following August saw the Atlantic Conference between American President Franklin Roosevelt and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, which defined a common Anglo-American vision of the post-war world, as formalized by the Atlantic Charter.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the Second Inter-Allied Meeting in London in September 1941, the Soviet Union joined the other Allies in adopting the Atlantic Charter.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 7–8 December, Japan attacked American and British territories in Asia and the Pacific, resulting in the US entering the war as an Allied power.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] China, which had been resisting a Japanese invasion since 1937, formally declared war on the Axis on 9 December.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Winston Churchill called the association of the United Kingdom, United States, Soviet Union and other Allies the "Grand Alliance".
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The "Big Three"—the United Kingdom, United States and Soviet Union—were the principal contributors of manpower, resources and strategy, each playing a key role in achieving victory.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States also saw China and its leader Chiang Kai-shek as its main ally in Asia and considered it one of the "Big Four" allied powers, a view not always shared by the United Kingdom and Soviet Union.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In December 1941, at the First Washington Conference, Roosevelt proposed the name "United Nations" for the Allies and Churchill agreed.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 1 January 1942, Roosevelt, Churchill and representatives of the Soviet Union and China signed the Declaration by United Nations.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The following day, representatives of 22 other allied countries signed the declaration.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Free French were not invited to sign because the United States recognized the Vichy government in France.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] From this time, countries that adopted the declaration were considered allies.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Mexico, the Philippines and Ethiopia adopted the declaration later in 1942, followed by Iraq, Brazil, Bolivia, Iran and Colombia in 1943, and Liberia in February 1944.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the liberation of France, the French provisional government signed the declaration on 26 December 1944 and France officially became one of the allied nations.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Eleven nations adhered to the declaration in early 1945, when an allied victory over Germany was assured and the Big Four powers were preparing to invite signatories to the San Francisco Conference to prepare a charter for the new United Nations organization.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] A series of conferences between the major allied leaders, diplomats, and military officials shaped the strategic direction of the war and the post-war international order.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Churchill and Roosevelt attended the first Washington Conference (December 1941 – January 1942) where they established the Combined Chiefs of Staff Committee and agreed to prioritize the European and North African theatres in the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Churchill and Roosevelt met again at Casablanca (January 1943) and Washington (May 1943) where they decided on an invasion of Sicily, the postponement of a landing in France until May 1944, and began planning a counter-offensive against Japan in Asia and the Pacific.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the first Quebec Conference (August 1943) Churchill and Roosevelt agreed to a new command structure in South-East Asia.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Churchill, Roosevelt and Chiang met at the Cairo Conference (November 1943) where they discussed operations against Japan and issued the Cairo Declaration outlining their vision for post-war Asia whereby Japan would lose all the territories it had gained since 1914.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Stalin declined to attend or send representatives as the Soviet Union was not at war with Japan.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Churchill, Roosevelt and Stalin met for the first time at the Tehran Conference (November – December 1943) where they decided that the full-scale offensive in France in mid-1944 was the allied priority and where Stalin announced that he would declare war on Japan once Hitler was defeated.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the Yalta Conference (February 1945) Churchill, Roosevelt and Stalin agreed to zones of occupation for the soon-to-be-defeated Germany and made plans for the post-war settlement of Europe and the United Nations organization.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the allied victory in Europe, the new US president, Harry S.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Truman, and new British prime minister, Clement Attlee, attended the final summit of the Big Three leaders at Potsdam (July – August 1945) where they discussed the final operations against Japan and issued a demand for its unconditional surrender.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Relations between the United Kingdom and United States were especially close.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Before they were formally allied, they had cooperated in a number of ways, notably through the destroyers-for-bases deal in September 1940 and the American Lend-Lease program, which provided Britain and the other allies with war materiel from March 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The British Commonwealth and empire obtained about half of the $42 to $50 billion in lend-lease aid during the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The British Commonwealth and, to a lesser extent, the French empire and Soviet Union reciprocated with a smaller Reverse Lend-Lease program worth about $8 billion.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] After the United States entered the war, the United Kingdom and the United States established a Combined Chiefs of Staff to harmonize military planning, and Combined Boards to co-ordinate shipping, raw materials, and war production.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Churchill and Roosevelt also met nine times in conferences without the presence of the other Big Four leaders.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the First Washington Conference, held soon after the United States entered the war, they agreed that Germany should be first defeated before focusing their forces on Japan.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Nevertheless, divisions between the United Kingdom and United States soon arose over strategy for the defeat of Germany.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] American planners pushed for a landing in France in 1942 followed by a full scale invasion 1943.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain, however, argued that an early invasion of France risked being repulsed with heavy allied losses.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Instead, they argued for weakening Germany through strategic bombing and economic warfare and dispersing Axis forces by opening fronts in French north Africa, Italy, and possibly the Balkans.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States and United Kingdom ultimately agreed to delay a full scale of invasion of France until May or June 1944, which angered Stalin because the Soviet Union was suffering heavy losses on its front with Germany.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] There were also significant disagreements between the United Kingdom and United States about the Asia-Pacific front.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] While Churchill prioritized the recovery of British imperial possessions such as Burma, Malaya, Hong Kong and Singapore, the Americans were more focused on supporting China by reopening its overland supply lines from India through the Burma road.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Roosevelt and Chiang were hostile to imperialism and pressed Churchill to reach an agreement with the leaders of the Indian independence movement and to agree to post-war mandates for British and French imperial possessions to prepare them for full independence.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Despite their ideological differences and severe tensions over the timing of an invasion of France, the Soviet Union and its western allies cooperated in a number of ways.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On the political front, the Soviet Union signed the Anglo-Soviet Agreement in July 1941, endorsed the Atlantic Charter in September, signed the Declaration by United Nations in January 1942, the Anglo-Soviet Treaty in May 1942, and the Four Powers Declaration in October 1943.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In May 1943, Stalin agreed to dissolve the Comintern as a gesture of goodwill.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On the strategic front, the Soviet Union, United Kingdom and United States agreed at the Tehran conference of late 1943 that an invasion of France was the military priority for 1944.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On the military front, in August 1941, British and Soviet forces invaded neutral Iran, which they suspected was pro-Axis, to secure oil supplies and the overland supply route into the Soviet Union.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The western allies sought to relieve pressure on the Soviet front by its strategic bombing campaign and economic warfare on Germany and by diverting Axis forces to the north African and Italian fronts.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Western food and materiel aid to the Soviet Union was also of great importance.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States supplied the Soviet Union with $10 billion worth of aid under lend-lease: equivalent to 7% of Soviet war production.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union, in turn, prosecuted the bulk of the ground war in which an estimated 5 million Axis soldiers were killed or missing in action on the eastern front.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] A rift developed between the Soviet Union and the western allies over the political settlement of postwar Europe.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union pressed the United Kingdom and United States to recognise the territorial gains it had made in the Baltic states, Finland, Bessarabia and eastern Poland before the German invasion.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United Kingdom and United States rejected these demands as incompatible with the Atlantic Charter principle of no territorial changes without the consent of the people concerned.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Despite their remaining differences over the borders and political future of the territories they occupied, the Big Three alliance held to the end of the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 8 August 1945, six days before Japan's surrender, the Soviet Union honoured its commitment to enter the war against Japan.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Roosevelt viewed China as an important ally in the war against Japan and as a potential counterweight to Soviet influence in the postwar world.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States saw allied military bases in China as staging posts for an eventual invasion of Japan and, in the meantime, Chinese nationalist forces tied up 500,000 to 600,000 Japanese troops in central China.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States provided loans and lend-lease aid to the nationalist government and, in December 1941, Chiang was named Supreme Allied Commander for China, Thailand and Indo-China.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In October 1942, the United States and United Kingdom agreed to relinquish their territorial concessions and other privileges under their unequal treaties with China.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In October 1943, the United States, United Kingdom, Soviet Union and China signed the Four Power Declaration in which they pledged to cooperate against their common enemies and establish an international organization for peace and security.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the Tehran Conference later that year, Roosevelt outlined his vision of China as one of the "four policemen" of the postwar world.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Senior officials in the Big Three powers, however, were critical of the corruption and inefficiency of the nationalist government and its military forces.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] There were also strategic differences between Chiang, who wanted a higher priority on the war against Japan, and the Big Three leaders who had agreed on a policy of defeating Germany first.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Relations between Chiang and his American chief-of-staff Joseph Stilwell were particularly tense.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Stilwell believed the Chinese forces lacked adequate training, supplies and leadership, while Chiang blamed Stilwell's insistence on diverting Chinese forces to the Burma campaign for the collapse of the nationalist army during Japan's China offensive of 1944.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Chiang's standing with the other allied leaders was weakened by the poor performance of his army during this offensive and by the US adoption of the island hopping strategy against Japan which reduced the importance of bases in China.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Chiang was not invited to the Yalta and Potsdam conferences of 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the outbreak of the war, the British Empire comprised over 60 countries including the dominions, India, Burma, and numerous Crown colonies and protectorates.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following Britain's declaration of war on Germany on 3 September 1939, most of the empire was automatically at war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, the dominions of Australia, Canada, New Zealand and South Africa separately declared war in the following two weeks.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the defeat of Poland in October 1939 and of France in June 1940, the UK took the lead in coordinating the war effort of its empire and the allied governments-in-exile in London.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] When the Soviet Union joined the Allies after the Axis invasion of June 1941 and the United States and China joined in December that year, the UK was the de facto representative of the empire and allied governments-in-exile in their dealings with the other Big Four powers.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain sustained its war effort by drawing on the population, raw material and strategic bases of its colonies throughout the world.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1939, the population of the empire, including the dominions, was about 484 million, making it the second most populous belligerent after China.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain’s colonies accounted for 42% of the empire’s economic output.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] After Japan occupied most of Britain's Asia-Pacific colonies – including Hong Kong, Burma, Malaya and Singapore – from December 1941, Britain expanded the production of food and manufacturing in India and the African colonies.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain’s colonies also made a significant contribution to the allied military effort.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] By 1945, 25% of the allied South-East Asia Command was African and about 4% of the empire's military dead were from the colonies other than India.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1939 Britain had the second largest navy and largest merchant navy in the world, and these played a vital role in transporting troops, armaments, food and raw materials for the Allies.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The British military played a major role in defeating the Axis powers in North Africa, Italy and the Western Front British and colonial troops also cleared Japanese forces from Burma.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain and the United States conducted the Combined Bomber Offensive against Germany from 1943 which diverted German resources from the Eastern Front and retarded German war production.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] About two-thirds of India was under the direct rule of the United Kingdom exercised by a viceroy representing the British crown.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The other third mostly consisted of princely states, nominally under Indian rulers subordinate to the British crown.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Nevertheless, India separately signed the Declaration by United Nations on 2 January 1942, and signed the Paris Peace Treaties of February 1947 as an Allied Power.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] India was an important supply base for Commonwealth, American and Chinese forces and itself produced about £286.5 million worth of military equipment and other supplies.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] By 1945, the Indian army numbered 2.5 million people – the largest volunteer army in history.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Indian troops played a major role in the Burma campaign and in other theaters.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Its military losses were about 100,000 killed, wounded or missing, and almost 80,000 taken prisoner.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] An estimated 3 million Indian people died in the Bengal famine of 1943.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] After Germany invaded Poland, France declared war on Germany on 3 September 1939.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Africa these included: French West Africa, French Equatorial Africa, the League of Nations mandates of French Cameroun and French Togoland, French Madagascar, French Somaliland, and the protectorates of French Tunisia and French Morocco.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] French Algeria was then not a colony or dependency but a fully-fledged part of metropolitan France.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Asia and Oceania France has several territories: French Polynesia, Wallis and Futuna, New Caledonia, the New Hebrides, French Indochina, French India, Guangzhouwan, the mandates of Greater Lebanon and French Syria.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The French government in 1936 attempted to grant independence to its mandate of Syria in the Franco-Syrian Treaty of Independence of 1936 signed by France and Syria.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, opposition to the treaty grew in France and the treaty was not ratified.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Syria had become an official republic in 1930 and was largely self-governing.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1941, a British-led invasion supported by Free French forces expelled Vichy French forces in Operation Exporter.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] France had several colonies in America, namely Martinique, Guadeloupe, French Guiana and Saint Pierre and Miquelon.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the lead-up to the war between the Soviet Union and Nazi Germany, relations between the two states underwent several stages.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] General Secretary Joseph Stalin and the government of the Soviet Union had supported so-called popular front movements of anti-fascists including communists and non-communists from 1935 to 1939.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The popular front strategy was terminated from 1939 to 1941, when the Soviet Union cooperated with Germany in 1939 in the occupation and partitioning of Poland.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet leadership refused to endorse either the Allies or the Axis from 1939 to 1941, as it called the Allied-Axis conflict an "imperialist war".
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Stalin had studied Hitler, including reading *Mein Kampf*, and from it knew of Hitler's motives for destroying the Soviet Union.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, Poland withdrew from the negotiations following German and Finnish objections.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union and Germany at this time competed with each other for influence in Poland.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 20 August 1939, forces of the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics under General Georgy Zhukov, together with the People's Republic of Mongolia eliminated the threat of conflict in the east with a victory over Imperial Japan at the Battle of Khalkhin Gol in eastern Mongolia.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On the same day, Soviet party leader Joseph Stalin received a telegram from German Chancellor Adolf Hitler, suggesting that German Foreign Minister Joachim von Ribbentrop fly to Moscow for diplomatic talks.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 15 September 1939, Stalin concluded a durable ceasefire with Japan, to take effect the following day (it would be upgraded to a non-aggression pact in April 1941).
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The day after that, 17 September, Soviet forces invaded Poland from the east.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Although some fighting continued until 5 October, the two invading armies held at least one joint military parade on 25 September, and reinforced their non-military partnership with the German–Soviet Treaty of Friendship, Cooperation and Demarcation on 28 September.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] German and Soviet cooperation against Poland in 1939 has been described as co-belligerence.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 30 November, the Soviet Union attacked Finland, for which it was expelled from the League of Nations.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the following year of 1940, while the world's attention was focused upon the German invasion of France and Norway, the Soviet Union militarily occupied and annexed Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania as well as parts of Romania.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] German-Soviet treaties were brought to an end by the German surprise attack on the Soviet Union on 22 June 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] After the invasion of the Soviet Union in 1941, Stalin endorsed the Western Allies as part of a renewed popular front strategy against Germany and called for the international communist movement to make a coalition with all those who opposed the Nazis.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union soon entered in alliance with the United Kingdom.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the Soviet Union, a number of other communist, pro-Soviet or Soviet-controlled forces fought against the Axis powers during the Second World War.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Among the Soviet forces during World War II, millions of troops were from the Soviet Central Asian Republics.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] They included 1,433,230 soldiers from Uzbekistan, more than 1 million from Kazakhstan, and more than 700,000 from Azerbaijan, among other Central Asian Republics.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States had indirectly supported Britain's war effort against Germany up to 1941 and declared its opposition to territorial aggrandizement.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Materiel support to Britain was provided while the U.S. was officially neutral via the Lend-Lease Act starting in 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Roosevelt and Prime Minister Winston Churchill in August 1941 promulgated the Atlantic Charter that pledged commitment to achieving "the final destruction of Nazi tyranny".
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Signing the Atlantic Charter, and thereby joining the "United Nations" was the way a state joined the Allies, and also became eligible for membership in the United Nations world body that formed in 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States strongly supported the Nationalist Government in China in its war with Japan, and provided military equipment, supplies, and volunteers to the Nationalist Government of China to assist in its war effort.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In December 1941 Japan opened the war with its attack on Pearl Harbor, the United States declared war on Japan, and Japan's allies Germany and Italy declared war on the United States, bringing the United States into World War II.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States played a central role in liaising among the Allies and especially among the Big Four.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the Arcadia Conference in December 1941, shortly after the United States entered the war, the United States and Britain established a Combined Chiefs of Staff, based in Washington, which deliberated the military decisions of both the United States and Britain.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 8 December 1941, following the attack on Pearl Harbor, the United States Congress declared war on Japan at the request of President Franklin D.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] This was followed by Germany and Italy declaring war on the United States on 11 December, bringing the country into the European theatre.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States led Allied forces in the Pacific theatre against Japanese forces from 1941 to 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] From 1943 to 1945, the United States also led and coordinated the Western Allies' war effort in Europe under the leadership of General Dwight D.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] American naval forces attained some early successes against Japan.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] One was the bombing of Japanese industrial centres in the Doolittle Raid.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Another was repelling a Japanese invasion of Port Moresby in New Guinea during the Battle of the Coral Sea.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] However American forces managed to sink four of Japan's six large aircraft carriers that had initiated the attack on Pearl Harbor along with other attacks on Allied forces.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Afterwards, the United States began an offensive against Japanese-captured positions.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Guadalcanal Campaign from 1942 to 1943 was a major contention point where Allied and Japanese forces struggled to gain control of Guadalcanal.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States held multiple dependencies in the Americas, such as Alaska, the Panama Canal Zone, Puerto Rico, and the U.S.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the Pacific it held multiple island dependencies such as American Samoa, Guam, Hawaii, Midway Islands, Wake Island and others.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] These dependencies were directly involved in the Pacific campaign of the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Commonwealth of the Philippines was a sovereign protectorate referred to as an "associated state" of the United States.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] From late 1941 to 1944, the Philippines was occupied by Japanese forces, who established the Second Philippine Republic as a client state that had nominal control over the country.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the 1920s the Soviet Union provided military assistance to the Kuomintang, or the Nationalists, and helped reorganize their party along Leninist lines: a unification of party, state, and army.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In exchange the Nationalists agreed to let members of the Chinese Communist Party join the Nationalists on an individual basis.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, following the nominal unification of China at the end of the Northern Expedition in 1928, Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek purged leftists from his party and fought against the revolting Chinese Communist Party, former warlords, and other militarist factions.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] A fragmented China provided easy opportunities for Japan to gain territories piece by piece without engaging in total war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the 1931 Mukden Incident, the puppet state of Manchukuo was established.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Throughout the early to mid-1930s, Chiang's anti-communist and anti-militarist campaigns continued while he fought small, incessant conflicts against Japan, usually followed by unfavorable settlements and concessions after military defeats.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1936 Chiang was forced to cease his anti-communist military campaigns after his kidnap and release by Zhang Xueliang, and reluctantly formed a nominal alliance with the Communists, while the Communists agreed to fight under the nominal command of the Nationalists against the Japanese.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the Marco Polo Bridge Incident of 7 July 1937, China and Japan became embroiled in a full-scale war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union, wishing to keep China in the fight against Japan, supplied China with military assistance until 1941, when it signed a non-aggression pact with Japan.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In December 1941 after the attack on Pearl Harbor, China formally declared war on Japan, as well as Germany and Italy.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] As part of the war's Pacific theater, China became the only member of the Allies to commit more troops than one of the Big Three, exceeding even the number of Soviet troops on the Eastern Front.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Prior to the alliance of Germany and Italy to Japan, the Nationalist Government held close relations with both Germany and Italy.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the early 1930s, Sino-German cooperation existed between the Nationalist Government and Germany in military and industrial matters.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Nazi Germany provided the largest proportion of Chinese arms imports and technical expertise.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Up until 1936, Mussolini had provided the Nationalists with Italian military air and naval missions to help the Nationalists fight against Japanese incursions and communist insurgents.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Italy also held strong commercial interests and a strong commercial position in China supported by the Italian concession in Tianjin.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Nationalist Government held close relations with the United States.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States opposed Japan's invasion of China in 1937 that it considered an illegal violation of China's sovereignty, and offered the Nationalist Government diplomatic, economic, and military assistance during its war against Japan.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In November 1940, American military aviator Claire Lee Chennault upon observing the dire situation in the air war between China and Japan, set out to organize a volunteer squadron of American fighter pilots to fight alongside the Chinese against Japan, known as the Flying Tigers.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Roosevelt accepted dispatching them to China in early 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, they only became operational shortly after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union recognised the Republic of China but urged reconciliation with the Chinese Communist Party and inclusion of Communists in the government.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union also urged military and cooperation between Nationalist China and Communist China during the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Even though China had been fighting the longest among all the Allied powers, it only officially joined the Allies after the attack on Pearl Harbor, on 7 December 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] China fought the Japanese Empire before joining the Allies in the Pacific War.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek thought Allied victory was assured with the entrance of the United States into the war, and he declared war on Germany and the other Axis states.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, Allied aid remained low because the Burma Road was closed and the Allies suffered a series of military defeats against Japan early on in the campaign.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] General Sun Li-jen led the R.O.C. forces to the relief of 7,000 British forces trapped by the Japanese in the Battle of Yenangyaung.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] He then reconquered North Burma and re-established the land route to China by the Ledo Road.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] But the bulk of military aid did not arrive until the spring of 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] More than 1.5 million Japanese troops were trapped in the China Theatre, troops that otherwise could have been deployed elsewhere if China had collapsed and made a separate peace.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] This was continued into the 1930s that fell in line with the Soviet Union's subversion policy of popular fronts to increase communists' influence in governments.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union urged military and cooperation between Communist China and Nationalist China during China's war against Japan.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Initially Mao Zedong accepted the demands of the Soviet Union and in 1938 had recognized Chiang Kai-shek as the "leader" of the "Chinese people".
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] In turn, the Soviet Union accepted Mao's tactic of "continuous guerilla warfare" in the countryside that involved a goal of extending the Communist bases, even if it would result in increased tensions with the Nationalists.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Communist Party's position in China was boosted further upon the Soviet invasion of Manchuria in August 1945 against the Japanese puppet state of Manchukuo and the Japanese Kwantung Army in China and Manchuria.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p01] Upon the intervention of the Soviet Union against Japan in World War II in 1945, Mao Zedong in April and May 1945 had planned to mobilize 150,000 to 250,000 soldiers from across China to work with forces of the Soviet Union in capturing Manchuria.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Australia was a sovereign Dominion under the Australian monarchy, as per the Statute of Westminster 1931.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] At the start of the war Australia followed Britain's foreign policies and accordingly declared war against Germany on 3 September 1939.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Australian foreign policy became more independent after the Australian Labor Party formed government in October 1941, and Australia separately declared war against Finland, Hungary and Romania on 8 December 1941 and against Japan the next day.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Before the war, Belgium had pursued a policy of neutrality and only became an Allied member after being invaded by Germany on 10 May 1940.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] During the ensuing fighting, Belgian forces fought alongside French and British forces against the invaders.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] While the British and French were struggling against the fast German advance elsewhere on the front, the Belgian forces were pushed into a pocket to the north.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] On 28 May, the King Leopold III surrendered himself and his military to the Germans, having decided the Allied cause was lost.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The legal Belgian government was reformed as a government in exile in London.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Belgian troops and pilots continued to fight on the Allied side as the Free Belgian Forces.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Belgium itself was occupied, but a sizeable Resistance was formed and was loosely coordinated by the government in exile and other Allied powers.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] British and Canadian troops arrived in Belgium in September 1944 and the capital, Brussels, was liberated on 6 September.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Because of the Ardennes Offensive, the country was only fully liberated in early 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Belgium held the colony of the Belgian Congo and the League of Nations mandate of Ruanda-Urundi.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Belgian Congo was not occupied and remained loyal to the Allies as an important economic asset while its deposits of uranium were useful to the Allied efforts to develop the atomic bomb.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Troops from the Belgian Congo participated in the East African Campaign against the Italians.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The colonial *Force Publique* also served in other theatres including Madagascar, the Middle-East, India and Burma within British units.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Initially, Brazil maintained a position of neutrality, trading with both the Allies and the Axis, while Brazilian president Getúlio Vargas's quasi-Fascist policies indicated a leaning toward the Axis powers.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] However, as the war progressed, trade with the Axis countries became almost impossible and the United States initiated forceful diplomatic and economic efforts to bring Brazil onto the Allied side.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] At the beginning of 1942, Brazil permitted the United States to set up air bases on its territory, especially in Natal, strategically located at the easternmost corner of the South American continent, and on 28 January the country severed diplomatic relations with Germany, Japan and Italy.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] After that, 36 Brazilian merchant ships were sunk by the German and Italian navies, which led the Brazilian government to declare war against Germany and Italy on 22 August 1942.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Brazil then sent a 25,700 strong Expeditionary Force to Europe that fought mainly on the Italian front, from September 1944 to May 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Also, the Brazilian Navy and Air Force acted in the Atlantic Ocean from the middle of 1942 until the end of the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Brazil was the only South American country to send troops to fight in the European theatre in the Second World War.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Canada was a sovereign Dominion under the Canadian monarchy, as per the Statute of Westminster 1931.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] In a symbolic statement of autonomous foreign policy Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King delayed parliament's vote on a declaration of war for seven days after Britain had declared war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Canada was the last member of the Commonwealth to declare war on Germany on 10 September 1939.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Cuba declared war on the Axis powers in December 1941, making it one of the first Latin American countries to enter the conflict, and by the war's end in 1945 its military had developed a reputation as being the most efficient and cooperative of all the Caribbean states.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] On 15 May 1943, the Cuban patrol boat CS-13 sank the German submarine *U-176*.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 1938, with the Munich Agreement, Czechoslovakia, the United Kingdom, and France sought to resolve German irredentist claims to the Sudetenland region.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] As a result, the incorporation of the Sudetenland into Germany began on 1 October 1938.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Additionally, a small northeastern part of the border region known as Trans-Olza was occupied by and annexed to Poland.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Further, by the First Vienna Award, Hungary received southern territories of Slovakia and Carpathian Ruthenia.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] A Slovak State was proclaimed on 14 March 1939, and the next day Hungary occupied and annexed the remainder of Carpathian Ruthenia, and the German *Wehrmacht* moved into the remainder of the Czech Lands.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] On 16 March 1939 the Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia was proclaimed after negotiations with Emil Hácha, who remained technically head of state with the title of State President.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] After a few months, former Czechoslovak President Beneš organized a committee in exile and sought diplomatic recognition as the legitimate government of the First Czechoslovak Republic.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The committee's success in obtaining intelligence and coordinating actions by the Czechoslovak resistance led first Britain and then the other Allies to recognize it in 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] In December 1941 the Czechoslovak government-in-exile declared war on the Axis powers.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Czechoslovak military units took part in the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Dominican Republic was one of the very few countries willing to accept mass Jewish immigration during World War II.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] At the Évian Conference, it offered to accept up to 100,000 Jewish refugees.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The DORSA (Dominican Republic Settlement Association) was formed with the assistance of the JDC, and helped settle Jews in Sosúa, on the northern coast.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] About 700 European Jews of Ashkenazi Jewish descent reached the settlement where each family received 33 hectares (82 acres) of land, 10 cows (plus 2 additional cows per children), a mule and a horse, and a US$10,000 loan (equivalent to about $219,000 in 2025) at 1% interest.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Dominican Republic officially declared war on the Axis powers on 11 December 1941, after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] However, the Caribbean state had already been engaged in war actions since before the formal declaration of war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Although the crew of *San Rafael* managed to escape the event, it would be remembered by the Dominican press as a sign of the "infamy of the German submarines and the danger they represented in the Caribbean".
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Many of them received medals and other recognitions for their outstanding actions in combat.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Kingdom of Egypt had been nominally an independent state since 1922 but, under the Anglo-Egyptian treaty of 1936, British forces were permitted in Egypt to defend the Suez Canal, the major trade route between the United Kingdom, India and Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] On 1 September 1939, Britain invoked another clause in the treaty allowing Britain to effectively occupy the country in the event of war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Although Egypt subsequently severed diplomatic relations with Germany, Italy and Vichy France, it remained formally neutral, even after Italy invaded the country on 17 September 1940.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Britain considered King Farouk an Axis sympathiser and, in the Abdeen Palace incident of February 1942, forced him to appoint a pro-British government which clamped down on Axis sympathisers.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Allied victory at the Second Battle of El Alamein in November 1942, secured Egypt from the Axis.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] On 26 February 1945, Egypt declared war on Germany and Japan, and the following day signed the United Nations declaration.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Ethiopian Empire was invaded by Italy on 3 October 1935.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] On 2 May 1936, Emperor Haile Selassie I fled into exile, just before the Italian occupation on 7 May.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] After the outbreak of World War II, the Ethiopian government-in-exile cooperated with the British during the British Invasion of Italian East Africa beginning in June 1940.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Haile Selassie returned to his rule on 18 January 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Ethiopia declared war on Germany, Italy and Japan in December 1942.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Greece was invaded by Italy on 28 October 1940 and subsequently joined the Allies.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Greek Army managed to stop the Italian offensive from Italy's protectorate of Albania, and Greek forces pushed Italian forces back into Albania.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] However, after the German invasion of Greece in April 1941, German forces managed to occupy mainland Greece and, a month later, the island of Crete.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Greek government went into exile, while the country was placed under a puppet government and divided into occupation zones run by Italy, Germany and Bulgaria.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] From 1941, a strong resistance movement appeared, chiefly in the mountainous interior, where it established a "Free Greece" by mid-1943.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Following the Italian capitulation in September 1943, the Italian zone was taken over by the Germans.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Axis forces left mainland Greece in October 1944, although some Aegean islands, notably Crete, remained under German occupation until the end of the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Before the war, Luxembourg had pursued a policy of neutrality and only became an Allied member after being invaded by Germany on 10 May 1940.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The government in exile fled, winding up in England.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] It made Luxembourgish language broadcasts to the occupied country on BBC Radio.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 1944, the government in exile signed a treaty with the Belgian and Dutch governments, creating the Benelux Economic Union and also signed into the Bretton Woods system.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Mexico declared war on Germany in 1942 after German submarines attacked the Mexican oil tankers *Potrero del Llano* and *Faja de Oro* that were transporting crude oil to the United States.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] These attacks prompted President Manuel Ávila Camacho to declare war on the Axis powers.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Mexico formed the Escuadrón 201 fighter squadron as part of the Fuerza Aérea Expedicionaria Mexicana (FAEM—"Mexican Expeditionary Air Force").
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The squadron was attached to the 58th Fighter Group of the United States Army Air Forces and carried out tactical air support missions during the liberation of the main Philippine island of Luzon in the summer of 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Some 300,000 Mexican citizens went to the United States to work on farms and factories.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Some 15,000 U.S. nationals of Mexican origin and Mexican residents in the US enrolled in the US Armed Forces and fought in various fronts around the world.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Netherlands became an Allied member after being invaded on 10 May 1940 by Germany.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] During the ensuing campaign, the Netherlands were defeated and occupied by Germany.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Netherlands was liberated by Canadian, British, American and other allied forces during the campaigns of 1944 and 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Princess Irene Brigade, formed from escapees from the German invasion, took part in several actions in 1944 in Arromanches and in 1945 in the Netherlands.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Navy vessels saw action in the British Channel, the North Sea and the Mediterranean, generally as part of Royal Navy units.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Dutch airmen flying British aircraft participated in the air war over Germany.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Dutch East Indies (modern-day Indonesia) was the principal Dutch colony in Asia, and was seized by Japan in 1942.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] During the Dutch East Indies Campaign, the Netherlands played a significant role in the Allied effort to halt the Japanese advance as part of the American-British-Dutch-Australian (ABDA) Command.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The ABDA fleet finally encountered the Japanese surface fleet at the Battle of Java Sea, at which Doorman gave the order to engage.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] During the ensuing battle the ABDA fleet suffered heavy losses, and was mostly destroyed after several naval battles around Java; the ABDA Command was later dissolved.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Japanese finally occupied the Dutch East Indies in February–March 1942.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Dutch troops, aircraft and escaped ships continued to fight on the Allied side and also mounted a guerrilla campaign in Timor.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] New Zealand was a sovereign Dominion under the New Zealand monarchy, as per the Statute of Westminster 1931.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] It quickly entered World War II, officially declaring war on Germany on 3 September 1939, just hours after Britain.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Unlike Australia, which had felt obligated to declare war, as it also had not ratified the Statute of Westminster, New Zealand did so as a sign of allegiance to Britain, and in recognition of Britain's abandonment of its former appeasement policy, which New Zealand had long opposed.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Because of its strategic location for control of the sea lanes in the North Sea and the Atlantic, both the Allies and Germany worried about the other side gaining control of the neutral country.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Germany ultimately struck first with Operation Weserübung on 9 April 1940, resulting in the two-month-long Norwegian Campaign, which ended in a German victory and their war-long occupation of Norway.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Units of the Norwegian Armed Forces evacuated from Norway or raised abroad continued participating in the war from exile.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Norwegian merchant fleet, then the fourth largest in the world, was organized into Nortraship to support the Allied cause.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Nortraship was the world's largest shipping company, and at its height operated more than 1000 ships.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Norway was neutral when Germany invaded, and it is not clear when Norway became an Allied country.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Great Britain, France and Polish forces in exile supported Norwegian forces against the invaders but without a specific agreement.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Norway's cabinet signed a military agreement with Britain on 28 May 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] This agreement allowed all Norwegian forces in exile to operate under British command.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Norwegian troops in exile should primarily be prepared for the liberation of Norway, but could also be used to defend Britain.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] At the end of the war German forces in Norway surrendered to British officers on 8 May and allied troops occupied Norway until 7 June.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Invasion of Poland on 1 September 1939, started the war in Europe, and the United Kingdom and France declared war on Germany on 3 September.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Poland fielded the third biggest army among the European Allies, after the Soviet Union and United Kingdom, but before France.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Polish Army suffered a series of defeats in the first days of the invasion.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Soviet Union unilaterally considered the flight to Romania of President Ignacy Mościcki and Marshal Edward Rydz-Śmigły on 17 September as evidence of *debellatio* causing the extinction of the Polish state, and consequently declared itself allowed to invade Poland starting from the same day.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] However, the Red Army had invaded the Second Polish Republic several hours before the Polish president fled to Romania.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Soviets invaded on 17 September at 3 a.m., while president Mościcki crossed the Polish-Romanian border at 21:45 on the same day.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The formation of the Polish armed forces in France began as early as September 1939.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] By June 1940, their numbers had reached 85,000 soldiers.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] These forces took part in the Norwegian campaign and the Battle of France.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] After the defeat of France, the reconstitution of the Polish army had to start from scratch.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Polish pilots played a key role in the Battle of Britain, separate Polish units took part in the North African Campaign.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] After the conclusion of the Polish-Soviet agreement on 30 July 1941, the formation of the Polish army in the Soviet Union (II Corps) also began.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The II Corps, numbering 83,000 along with civilians, began to be evacuated from the Soviet Union in mid-1942.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] It later took part in the fighting in Italy.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] After breaking off relations with the Polish government, the Soviet Union began forming its own Polish communist government and its armed forces in mid-1943, from which the 1st Polish Army, under Zygmunt Berling, was formed on 16 March 1944.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] That army was fighting on the eastern front, alongside the Soviet forces, including the Battle of Berlin, the closing battle of the European theater of war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Home Army, loyal to the London-based government and the largest underground force in Europe, as well other smaller resistance organizations in occupied Poland provided intelligence to the Allies and led to uncovering of Nazi war crimes (i.e., death camps).
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Saudi Arabia severed diplomatic contacts with Germany on 11 September 1939, and with Japan in October 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Saudis provided the Allies with large supplies of oil.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Diplomatic relations with the United States were established in 1943.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] King Abdul Aziz Al-Saud was a personal friend of Franklin D.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Americans were then allowed to build an air force base near Dhahran.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Saudi Arabia declared war on Germany and Japan in 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] South Africa was a sovereign Dominion under the South African monarchy, as per the Statute of Westminster 1931.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] South Africa held authority over the mandate of South-West Africa.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Due to significant pro-German feeling and the presence of fascist sympathizers within the Afrikaner nationalist movement (such as the Grey Shirts and the Ossewabrandwag), South Africa's entry into the war was politically divisive.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Hertzog tried to maintain official neutrality after the outbreak of war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] This caused a revolt by the governing United Party caucus which voted against Hertzog's position on the war and resulted in Hertzog's coalition partner, Jan Smuts, forming a new government and becoming prime minister.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Smuts was then able to lead the country into war on the side of the Allies.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Around 334,000 South Africans volunteered to fight in the war with 11,023 recorded wartime deaths.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Yugoslavia entered the war on the Allied side after the invasion of Axis powers on 6 April 1941.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Royal Yugoslav Army was thoroughly defeated in less than two weeks and the country was occupied starting on 18 April.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Italian-backed Croatian fascist leader Ante Pavelić declared the Independent State of Croatia before the invasion was over.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] King Peter II and much of the Yugoslavian government had left the country.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] In the United Kingdom, they joined numerous other governments in exile from Nazi-occupied Europe.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Beginning with the uprising in Herzegovina in June 1941, there was continuous anti-Axis resistance in Yugoslavia until the end of the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Before the end of 1941, the anti-Axis resistance movement split between the royalist Chetniks and the communist Yugoslav Partisans of Josip Broz Tito who fought both against each other during the war and against the occupying forces.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Yugoslav Partisans managed to put up considerable resistance to the Axis occupation, forming various liberated territories during the war.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] In August 1943, there were over 30 Axis divisions on the territory of Yugoslavia, not including the forces of the Croatian puppet state and other quisling formations.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 1944, the leading Allied powers persuaded Tito's Yugoslav Partisans and the royalist Yugoslav government led by Prime Minister Ivan Šubašić to sign the Treaty of Vis that created the Democratic Federal Yugoslavia.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Partisans were a major Yugoslav resistance movement against the Axis occupation and partition of Yugoslavia.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Initially, the Partisans were in rivalry with the Chetniks over control of the resistance movement.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] However, the Partisans were recognized by both the Eastern and Western Allies as the primary resistance movement in 1943.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] After that, their strength increased rapidly, from 100,000 at the beginning of 1943 to over 648,000 in September 1944.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 1945 they were transformed into the Yugoslav army, organized in four field armies with 800,000 fighters.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Chetniks, the short name given to the movement titled the *Yugoslav Army of the Fatherland*, were initially a major Allied Yugoslav resistance movement.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] However, due to their royalist and anti-communist views, Chetniks were considered to have begun collaborating with the Axis as a tactical move to focus on destroying their Partisan rivals.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Chetniks presented themselves as a Yugoslav movement, but were primarily a Serb movement.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] They reached their peak in 1943 with 93,000 fighters.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Their major contribution was Operation Halyard in 1944.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] In collaboration with the OSS, 413 Allied airmen shot down over Yugoslavia were rescued and evacuated.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Italy invaded Albania on 7 April 1939 and annexed the country.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] King Zog of Albania fled to London, but Britain recognized the Italian annexation.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Various resistance groups emerged in Albania including the Balli Kombëtar (National Front) and partisans led by the Communist Party.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Following Italy's withdrawal from the Axis in September 1943, Germany invaded Albania and installed a new collaborationist government.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] In October 1944, Germany began evacuating Albania, harried by the partisans who, supplied by the Allies, were now the dominant resistance army.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Tirana fell to the partisans on 28 November 1944 and the Communist-dominated National Liberation Movement took control of the country.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Albania was recognized as an "Associated Power" of the Allies in the peace treaty with Italy of February 1947.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Bulgaria signed the Tripartite Pact on 1 March 1941, and on 13 December declared war on the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Bulgaria did not declare war on the Soviet Union, but as the Soviet army advanced to its border in 1944, it submitted to Soviet pressure and declared war on Germany on 8 September.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] A new Bulgarian government, dominated by communists, committed over 300,000 troops to the war against Germany.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] These troops fought alongside Soviet forces in the Balkans, Hungary and Austria.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Bulgaria remained technically at war with the Allies until the ratification of its treaty of February 1947 with them.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Finland was invaded by the Soviet Union on 30 November 1939 and forced to cede territory in the subsequent peace treaty of 12 March 1940.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] On 26 June 1941, Finland joined Germany in its invasion of the Soviet Union, leading to the United Kingdom declaring war on Finland on 5 December.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Finland sought peace when Soviet troops entered the country in 1944.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Soviet Union demanded that Finland break off relations with Germany and expel or disarm German troops in Finland as preconditions for an armistice.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Finland severed relations with Germany on 3 September 1944, and signed the Moscow Armistice with the Soviet Union on 19 September.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Under pressure from the Soviet Union, Finland escalated skirmishing with the German troops evacuating Finland into warfare in the Lapland region by 2 October.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Finland's war against Germany ended when the last German soldiers left Finland for Norway in April 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Finland, however, was not recognised as an allied power.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] It remained technically at war with the Soviet Union and United Kingdom until ratification of its 1947 peace treaty with them.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Italy entered the war as an Axis power on 10 June 1940.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Following the Allied invasion of Sicily, Italy's fascist leader Benito Mussolini was deposed on 25 July 1943, and the Italian king, Victor Emmanuel III, appointed Pietro Badoglio prime minister.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The new government signed an armistice on 3 September 1943 ending Italy's war against the Allies.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Italian government moved to the south of the country and declared war on Germany on 13 October, becoming a co-belligerent of the Allies.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Italian Co-Belligerent Army participated in the Allied campaign against German forces in Italy and Mussolini's Italian Social Republic in the north of the country.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The co-belligerent army's participation in the fighting was initially limited until, in January 1945, four divisions were deployed on the frontline from Bologna to the Adriatic.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Italy remained technically at war with the Allies until ratification of its 1947 peace treaty with the Allied and Associated Powers.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Initially neutral in the war, Romania joined the Axis powers when it signed the Tripartite Pact on 23 November 1940.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] It joined the German invasion of the Soviet Union on 22 June 1941, leading to the United Kingdom declaring war on Romania on 7 December.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Romania declared war on the United States on 12 December.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] As the war turned against the Axis powers, King Michael of Romania deposed the government of Ion Antonescu on 23 August 1944, and Romania entered the war against Germany and Hungary.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Romania signed an armistice with the Allies on 12 September under which it was required to deploy 12 infantry divisions against the remaining Axis powers.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Romania eventually deployed 16 to 20 divisions, assisting the Soviet Union in driving Axis forces from Romania, Hungary and Czechoslovakia.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Romanian army was the fourth largest engaged against Axis forces in Europe at that time.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Soviet Union compelled the Romanian government of Petru Groza to demobilise its forces in March 1945, and Romania remained formally at war with the Allies until the ratification of its 1947 peace treaty with them.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Declaration by United Nations on 1 January 1942, signed by the Four Policemen – the United States, United Kingdom, Soviet Union and China – and 22 other countries laid the groundwork for the future of the United Nations.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] At the Potsdam Conference of July – August 1945, Roosevelt's successor, Harry S.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Charter of the United Nations was agreed to during the war at the United Nations Conference on International Organization, held between April and July 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Charter was signed by 50 states on 26 June (Poland had its place reserved and later became the 51st "original" signatory), and was formally ratified shortly after the war on 24 October 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Security Council met for the first time in the immediate aftermath of war on 17 January 1946.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] Despite the successful creation of the United Nations, the alliance of the Soviet Union with the United States and with the United Kingdom ultimately broke down and evolved into the Cold War, which took place over the following half-century.
[src:chuuk-state/allies-of-world-war-ii-p02] The following list denotes dates on which states declared war on the Axis powers, or on which an Axis power declared war on them.
[src:chuuk-state/alonso-de-arellano] Arellano was captain of the *San Lucas*, piloted by Lope Martín, one of four ships in a fleet commanded by Miguel López de Legazpi.
[src:chuuk-state/alonso-de-arellano] The fleet sailed from Mexico on 21 November 1564, but the *San Lucas* became separated from the rest on 1 December.
[src:chuuk-state/alonso-de-arellano] Arellano continued onto the Philippines.
[src:chuuk-state/alonso-de-arellano] He discovered a number of islands in January 1565, including Lib, Truk, Pulap, and Ngulu, before sailing back to Mexico, becoming the first navigator to establish the "Urdaneta's Route" in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:chuuk-state/alonso-de-arellano] Andrés de Urdaneta was part of Legazpi's fleet, who had also separated from the group and discovered the same path afterwards.
[src:chuuk-state/alonso-de-arellano] Urdaneta kept better documents and maps of the voyage and so the credit was given to him by historians.
[src:chuuk-state/alonso-de-arellano] Arellano was detained after his return on suspicion of desertion from Legazpi's fleet; however, an enquiry was inconclusive.
[src:chuuk-state/alonso-de-arellano] Before his death, he wrote a narrative of his voyage; this was published in Spain in 1887.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] The exact date and place of his birth are unknown, but he was born in the late 15th century or early 16th century in Spain.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] Hernán Cortés was his relative, whom he accompanied to Mexico (New Spain) in 1526.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] In 1527, Hernán Cortés prepared a new expedition to search for the missing fleet of the Loaísa expedition and commissioned his cousin Álvaro to command the new expedition.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] However, the true purpose of the expedition was to find new lands in the South Sea (Pacific Ocean) and to bring back spice plants.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] On 31 October 1527, they sailed from Zihuatanejo, Guerrero.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] On 15 December, after having sailed 1,170 leagues (roughly 3,000 miles or 4,890 km), the *Espiritu Santo* and the *Santiago* swept on ahead, after a sudden squall, never to be heard of again.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] On 2 February 1528, the "La Florida" sighted the Philippines and the following day anchored at a small island off the north coast of Mindanao, after 95 days since its departure and having sailed 1923 leagues.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] On 30 March 1528, the "La Florida" arrived to Tidore, the Spanish stronghold in the Moluccas where the men remaining from the Loaisa expedition were found, and they joined them to fight the Portuguese in the neighbouring Ternate.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] To carry out the instructions of the expedition and bring further assistance to the Spaniards in Tidore, Saavedra set sail for New Spain on 14 June 1528.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] On 24 June 1528, the "La Florida" discovered the Schouten Islands and landed on Yapen.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] These were charted respectively as "Islas de Oro" (Golden Islands) and "Payne" Island.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] They continued coasting western New Guinea until discovering the Admiralty Islands on 15 August.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] Landing on Manus Island, they charted it as "Urays La Grande" (Urays the Big).
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] They then sailed north and discovered the Nomoi Islands in the Carolines.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] Then were next diverted by the northeast trade winds that threw them back to the Moluccas, returning to Tidore on 19 November 1528.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] On 3 May 1529, Álvaro de Saavedra tried again the second time by navigating back down south.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] Again he toured the western part of New Guinea getting to Manus Island, then heading north and discovering on 14 September Pohnpei and Ant in the Carolines.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] On 21 September, they discovered Ujelang Atoll, in the Marshalls that they charted as "Los Pintados" (The Painted Ones) because of its inhabitants being tattooed.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] On 1 October, they discovered Enewetak Atoll, that they named "Los Jardines" (The Gardens) because of their beauty and the friendliness of their inhabitants.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] Soon after Saavedra died, and Pedro Laso took command.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] They sailed north up to the 31N but not finding westerly winds and also after the death of Pedro Laso, they finally decided to turn around the ship and again return to the Moluccas, arriving to Halmahera next to Tidore on 8 December 1529.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] They were captured there by the Portuguese and held in captivity for five years.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] In 1534, the surviving eight members of his crew made it back to Spain.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] There are some questions as to whether Spanish explorers did arrive in the Hawaiian Islands two centuries before Captain James Cook's first recorded visit in 1778.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] For two and a half centuries Spanish galleons crossed the Pacific along a route that passed south of Hawaii on their way to Manila.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] The exact route was kept secret to protect the Spanish trade monopoly against competing powers.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] In the case of the Saavedra expedition, the sighting of Hawaii could have happened when on 28 November 1527, land was sighted to the north, approximately in the longitude of Hawaii but not found again after a two-days search.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] Also, the later disappeared *Santiago* and *Espíritu Santo* could have arrived in Hawaii.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] There is an old Hawaiian oral story of white people arriving on the islands many generations ago, and welcomed by Chief Wakalana.
[src:chuuk-state/alvaro-de-saavedra] It is possible that these visitors were crew members from Saavedra's expedition.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:chuuk-state/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They also include indigenous ethnic minorities in Vietnam, Cambodia, Myanmar, Thailand, Hainan, and the Torres Strait Islands.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The nations and territories predominantly populated by Austronesian-speaking peoples are sometimes known collectively as **Austronesia**.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The group originated from a prehistoric seaborne migration, known as the Austronesian expansion, from Taiwan, circa 3000 to 1500 BCE.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Austronesians reached the Batanes Islands in the northernmost Philippines by around 2200 BCE.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They used sails some time before 2000 BCE.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In conjunction with their use of other maritime technologies (notably catamarans, outrigger boats, lashed-lug boats, and the crab claw sail), this enabled phases of rapid dispersal into the islands of the Indo-Pacific, culminating in the settlement of New Zealand c.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] During the initial part of the migrations, they encountered and assimilated (or were assimilated by) the Paleolithic populations that had migrated earlier into Maritime Southeast Asia and New Guinea.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They reached as far as Easter Island to the east, Madagascar to the west, and New Zealand to the south.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] At the furthest extent, they might have also reached the Americas.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Aside from language, Austronesian peoples widely share cultural characteristics, including such traditions and traditional technologies as lashed-lug shipbuilding, tattooing, stilt houses, jade carving, wetland agriculture, and various rock art motifs.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They also share domesticated plants and animals that were carried along with the migrations, including rice, bananas, coconuts, breadfruit, *Dioscorea* yams, taro, paper mulberry, chickens, pigs, and dogs.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The linguistic connections between Madagascar, Polynesia, and Southeast Asia, particularly the similarities between Malagasy, Malay, and Polynesian numerals, were recognized early in the colonial era by European authors.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] German naturalist Johann Reinhold Forster, who traveled with James Cook on his second voyage, also recognized the similarities of Polynesian languages to those of Island Southeast Asia.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In his book *Observations Made during a Voyage round the World* (1778), he posited that the ultimate origins of the Polynesians might have been the lowland regions of the Philippines and proposed that they arrived to the islands via long-distance voyaging.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Multiple other authors corroborated this classification (except for the erroneous inclusion of Maldivian), and the language family came to be known as "Malayo-Polynesian", first coined by the German linguist Franz Bopp in 1841 (German: *malayisch-polynesisch*).
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The connections between Southeast Asia, Madagascar, and the Pacific Islands were also noted by other European explorers, including the Orientalist William Marsden and the naturalist Johann Reinhold Forster.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Johann Friedrich Blumenbach added Austronesians as the fifth category to his "varieties" of humans in the second edition of *De Generis Humani Varietate Nativa* (1781).
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] He initially grouped them by geography and thus called Austronesians the "people from the southern world".
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In the third edition, published in 1795, he named Austronesians the "Malay race", or the "brown race", after correspondence with Joseph Banks, who was part of the first voyage of James Cook.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Blumenbach used the term "Malay" due to his belief that most Austronesians spoke the "Malay idiom" (i.e., the Austronesian languages), though he inadvertently caused the later confusion of his racial category with the Malay ethnic group.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The other varieties Blumenbach identified were the "Caucasians" (white), "Mongolians" (yellow), "Ethiopians" (black), and "Americans" (red).
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Blumenbach's definition of the "Malay" race is largely identical to the modern distribution of the Austronesian peoples, including not only Islander Southeast Asians but also the people of Madagascar and the Pacific Islands.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Although Blumenbach's work was later used in scientific racism, Blumenbach was a monogenist and did not believe the human "varieties" were inherently inferior to each other.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Rather, he believed that the Malay race was a combination of the "Ethiopian" and "Caucasian" varieties.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] — Johann Friedrich Blumenbach,*The anthropological treatises of Johann Friedrich Blumenbach*, translated by Thomas Bendyshe, 1865.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] By the 19th century, however, a classification of Austronesians as being a subset of the "Mongolian" race was favored, as was polygenism.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The British naturalist James Cowles Prichard originally followed Blumenbach by treating Papuans and Indigenous Australians as being descendants of the same stock as Austronesians.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] But by his third edition of *Researches into the Physical History of Man* (1836–1847), his work had become more racialized due to the influence of polygenism.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] He classified the peoples of Austronesia into two groups: the "Malayo-Polynesians" (roughly equivalent to the Austronesian peoples) and the "Kelænonesians" (roughly equivalent to the Australo-Melanesians).
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] He further subdivided the latter into the "Alfourous" (also "Haraforas" or "Alfoërs", the Native Australians), and the "Pelagian or Oceanic Negroes" (the Melanesians and western Polynesians).
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Despite this, he acknowledges that "Malayo-Polynesians" and "Pelagian Negroes" had "remarkable characters in common", particularly in terms of language and craniometry.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In linguistics, the Malayo-Polynesian language family also initially excluded Melanesia and Micronesia, due to the perceived physical differences between the inhabitants of these regions from Malayo-Polynesian speakers.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, there was growing evidence of their linguistic relationship to Malayo-Polynesian languages, notably from studies on the Melanesian languages by Georg von der Gabelentz, Robert Henry Codrington, and Sidney Herbert Ray.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Codrington coined and used the term "Ocean" language family rather than "Malayo-Polynesian" in 1891, in opposition to the exclusion of Melanesian and Micronesian languages.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] This was adopted by Ray, who defined the "Oceanic" language family as encompassing the languages of Southeast Asia and Madagascar, Micronesia, Melanesia, and Polynesia.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In 1899, the Austrian linguist and ethnologist Wilhelm Schmidt coined the term "Austronesian" (German: *austronesisch*, from Latin *auster*, "south wind"; and Greek *νῆσος*, "island") to refer to the language family.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Schmidt had the same motivations as Codrington: he proposed the term as a replacement to "Malayo-Polynesian", because he also opposed the implied exclusion of the languages of Melanesia and Micronesia in the latter name.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] It became the accepted name for the language family, with Oceanic and Malayo-Polynesian languages being retained as names for subgroups.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The term "Austronesian", or more accurately "Austronesian-speaking peoples", came to refer to people who speak the languages of the Austronesian language family.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Some authors, however, object to the use of the term to refer to people, as they question whether there really is any biological or cultural shared ancestry between all Austronesian-speaking groups.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] This is especially true for authors who reject the prevailing "Out of Taiwan" hypothesis and instead offer scenarios where the Austronesian languages spread among preexisting static populations through borrowing or convergence, with little or no population movements.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Despite these objections, the general consensus is that the archeological, cultural, genetic, and especially linguistic evidence all separately indicate varying degrees of shared ancestry among Austronesian-speaking peoples that justifies their treatment as a "phylogenetic unit".
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] This has led to the use of the term "Austronesian" in academic literature to refer not only to the Austronesian languages but also the Austronesian-speaking peoples, their societies, and the geographic area of Austronesia.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Some Austronesian-speaking groups are not direct descendants of Austronesians and acquired their languages through language shift, but this is believed to have happened only in a few instances, since the Austronesian expansion was too rapid for language shifts to have occurred fast enough.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In parts of Island Melanesia, migrations and paternal admixture from Papuan groups after the Austronesian expansion (estimated to have started at around 500 BCE) also resulted in gradual population turnover.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These secondary migrations were incremental and happened gradually enough that the culture and language of these groups remained Austronesian, even though in modern times, they are genetically more Papuan.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In the vast majority of cases, the language and material culture of Austronesian-speaking groups descend directly through generational continuity, especially in islands that were previously uninhabited.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Serious research into the Austronesian languages and its speakers has been ongoing since the 19th century.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Modern scholarship on Austronesian dispersion models is generally credited to two influential papers in the late 20th century: *The Colonization of the Pacific: A Genetic Trail* (Hill & Serjeantson, eds., 1989) and *The Austronesian Dispersal and the Origin of Languages* (Bellwood, 1991).
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The topic is particularly interesting to scientists for the remarkably unique characteristics of the Austronesian speakers: their extent, diversity, and rapid dispersal.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Regardless, certain disagreements still exist among researchers with regards to chronology, origin, dispersal, adaptations to the island environments, interactions with preexisting populations in areas they settled, and cultural developments over time.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The mainstream accepted hypothesis is the "Out of Taiwan" model first proposed by Peter Bellwood.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] But there are multiple rival models that create a sort of "pseudo-competition" among their supporters due to narrow focus on data from limited geographic areas or disciplines.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The most notable of which is the "Out of Sundaland" (or "Out of Island Southeast Asia") model.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Austronesians were the first humans with seafaring vessels that could cross large distances on the open ocean; this technology allowed them to colonize a large part of the Indo-Pacific region.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Prior to the 16th-century colonial era, the Austronesian language family was the most widespread in the world, spanning half the planet from Easter Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean to Madagascar in the western Indian Ocean.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Languages of the Austronesian family are today spoken by about 386 million people (4.9% of the global population), making it the fifth-largest language family by number of speakers.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Major Austronesian languages include Malay (around 250–270 million in Indonesia alone in its own literary standard, named Indonesian), Javanese, and Filipino (Tagalog).
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The family contains 1,257 languages, the second-largest number of any language family.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The geographic region that encompasses native Austronesian-speaking populations is sometimes referred to as "Austronesia".
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In Indonesia, the nationalistic term Nusantara, from Old Javanese, is also popularly used for the Indonesian islands.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Austronesian regions are almost exclusively islands in the Pacific and Indian oceans, with predominantly tropical or subtropical climates with considerable seasonal rainfall.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Inhabitants of these regions include Taiwanese indigenous peoples, most ethnic groups in Brunei, East Timor, Indonesia, Madagascar, Malaysia, Micronesia, the Philippines, and Polynesia.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Also included are the Malays of Singapore; the Polynesians of New Zealand, Hawaii, and Chile; the Torres Strait Islanders of Australia; the non-Papuan peoples of Melanesia and coastal New Guinea; the Shibushi speakers of Mayotte, and the Malagasy and Shibushi speakers of Réunion.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Austronesians are also found in the regions of Southern Thailand; the Cham areas in Vietnam, Cambodia, and Hainan; and the Mergui Archipelago of Myanmar.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Additionally, modern-era migration has brought Austronesian-speaking people to the United States, Canada, Australia, the UK, mainland Europe, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, South Africa, Sri Lanka, Suriname, Hong Kong, Macau, and West Asian countries.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Some authors also propose further settlements and contacts in the past in areas that are not inhabited by Austronesian speakers today.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These range from likely hypotheses to very controversial claims with minimal evidence.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In 2009, Roger Blench compiled an expanded map of Austronesia that encompassed these claims based on a variety of evidence, such as historical accounts, loanwords, introduced plants and animals, genetics, archeological sites, and material culture.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They include areas like the Pacific coast of the Americas, Japan, the Yaeyama Islands, the Australian coast, Sri Lanka and coastal South Asia, the Persian Gulf, some Indian Ocean islands, East Africa, South Africa, and West Africa.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Austronesians also mixed with other preexisting populations as well as later migrant populations among the islands they settled, resulting in further genetic input.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The most notable are the Austroasiatic-speaking peoples in western Island Southeast Asia (peninsular Malaysia, Sumatra, Borneo, and Java); the Bantu peoples in Madagascar; as well as Japanese, Persian, Indian, Arab, and Han Chinese traders and migrants in more recent centuries.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Island Southeast Asia was settled by modern humans in the Paleolithic following coastal migration routes, presumably starting before 70,000 BP from Africa, long before the development of Austronesian cultures.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These populations are typified by having dark skin, curly hair, and short statures, leading Europeans to believe, in the 19th century, that they were related to African Pygmies.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, despite these physical similarities, genetic studies have shown that they are more closely related to other Eurasian populations than to Africans.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The lowered sea levels of the Pleistocene made some of the modern-day islands of Sundaland accessible via land bridges.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, the spread of humans across the Wallace line and into Sahul necessitated crossing bodies of water.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Remains of stone tools and marine shells in Liang Sarru, Salibabu Island, North Sulawesi, dated to 32,000–35,000 years ago, is possible evidence for the longest sea voyage by Paleolithic humans ever recorded.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The island was previously uninhabited by humans or hominins and can only be reached from either Mindanao or the Sangihe Islands by crossing an expanse of water at least 100 km (62 mi) wide, even during the low sea levels of the Pleistocene.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Other evidence of early maritime transport are the appearance of obsidian tools with the same source on neighboring islands.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These include the Philippine obsidian network (Mindoro and Palawan, ca.33,000-28,000 BP), and the Wallacea obsidian network (Timor, Atauro, Kisar, Alor, ca.22,000 BP).
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, the method of crossing remains unknown and could have ranged from simple rafts to dugout canoes by the terminal Pleistocene.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These early settlers are generally historically referred to as "Australo-Melanesians", though the terminology is problematic, as they are genetically diverse, and most groups within Austronesia have significant Austronesian admixture and culture.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The unmixed descendants of these groups today include the interior Papuans and Indigenous Australians.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In modern literature, descendants of these groups, located in Island Southeast Asia west of Halmahera, are usually collectively referred to as "Negritos", while descendants of these groups east of Halmahera (excluding Indigenous Australians) are referred to as "Papuans".
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They can also be divided into two broad groups based on Denisovan admixture.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Philippine Negritos, Papuans, Melanesians, and Indigenous Australians display Denisovan admixture, while Malaysian and western Indonesian Negritos (Orang Asli) and Andamanese islanders do not.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Mahdi (2017) also uses the term "Qata" (from Proto-Malayo-Polynesian *qata) to distinguish the indigenous populations of Southeast Asia, versus "Tau" (from Proto-Austronesian *Cau) for the later settlers from Taiwan and mainland China.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Both are based on proto-forms for the word "person" in Malayo-Polynesian languages that referred to darker-skinned and lighter-skinned groups, respectively.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Jinam *et al.* (2017) also proposed the term "First Sundaland People" in place of "Negrito", as a more accurate name for the original population of Southeast Asia.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These populations are genetically distinct from later Austronesians, but through fairly extensive population admixture, most modern Austronesians have varying levels of ancestry from these groups.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The same is true for some populations historically considered "non-Austronesians", due to physical differences—like Philippine Negritos, Orang Asli, and Austronesian-speaking Melanesians, all of whom have Austronesian admixture.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In Polynesians in Remote Oceania, for example, the admixture is around 20 to 30% Papuan and 70 to 80% Austronesian.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Melanesians in Near Oceania are roughly around 20% Austronesian and 80% Papuan, while in the natives of the Lesser Sunda Islands, the admixture is around 50% Austronesian and 50% Papuan.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Similarly, in the Philippines, the groups traditionally considered to be "Negrito" vary between 30 and 50% Austronesian.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The high degree of assimilation among Austronesian, Negrito, and Papuan groups indicates that the Austronesian expansion was largely peaceful.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Rather than violent displacement, the settlers and the indigenous groups absorbed each other.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] It is believed that in some cases, like in the Toalean culture of Sulawesi (c.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] 8,000–1,500 BP), it is even more accurate to say that the densely populated indigenous hunter-gatherer groups absorbed the incoming Austronesian farmers, rather than the other way around.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Mahdi (2016) further asserts that Proto-Malayo-Polynesian *tau-mata ("person") is derived from a composite protoform *Cau ma-qata, combining "Tau" and "Qata" and indicative of the mixing of the two ancestral population types in these regions.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The broad consensus on the Urheimat (homeland) of Austronesian languages as well as the Neolithic early Austronesian peoples is accepted to be Taiwan, as well as the Penghu Islands.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They are believed to have descended from ancestral populations in coastal mainland southern China, which are generally referred to as the "pre‑Austronesians".
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Through these pre-Austronesians, Austronesians may also share a common ancestry with neighboring groups in Neolithic southern China.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These Neolithic pre-Austronesians from the coast of southeastern China are believed to have migrated to Taiwan between approximately 10,000 and 6000 BCE.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Other research has suggested that, according to radiocarbon dates, Austronesians may have migrated from mainland China to Taiwan as late as 4000 BCE (Dapenkeng culture).
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They continued to maintain regular contact with the mainland until 1500 BCE.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The identity of the Neolithic pre-Austronesian cultures in China is contentious.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Tracing Austronesian prehistory in Fujian and Taiwan has been difficult due to the southward expansion of the Han dynasty (2nd century BCE) and the recent Qing dynasty annexation of Taiwan (1683 CE).
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Today, the only Austronesian language in southern China is Tsat, spoken in Hainan.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The politicization of archaeology is also problematic, particularly erroneous reconstructions among some Chinese archaeologists of non-Sinitic sites as Han.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Some authors, favoring the "Out of Sundaland" model, like William Meacham, reject the southern Chinese mainland origin of pre-Austronesians entirely.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Nevertheless, based on linguistic, archaeological, and genetic evidence, Austronesians are most strongly associated with the early farming cultures of the Yangtze River basin that domesticated rice from around 13,500 to 8,200 BP.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They display typical Austronesian technological hallmarks, including tooth removal, teeth blackening, jade carving, tattooing, stilt houses, advanced boatbuilding, aquaculture, wetland agriculture, and the domestication of dogs, pigs, and chickens.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These include the Kuahuqiao, Hemudu, Majiabang, Songze, Liangzhu, and Dapenkeng cultures that occupied the coastal regions between the Yangtze River delta and the Min River delta.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Based on linguistic evidence, there have been proposals linking Austronesians with other linguistic families into linguistic macrofamilies that are relevant to the identity of the pre-Austronesian populations.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The most notable are the connections of Austronesians to the neighboring Austroasiatic, Kra-Dai, and Sinitic peoples (as Austric, Austro-Tai, and Sino-Austronesian, respectively).
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These are still not widely accepted, as evidence of these relationships are still tenuous, and the methods used are highly contentious.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Under that view, there was an east–west genetic alignment, resulting from a rice-based population expansion, in the southern part of East Asia: Austroasiatic-Kra-Dai-Austronesian, with unrelated Sino-Tibetan occupying a more northerly tier.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Depending on the author, other hypotheses have also included other language families like Hmong–Mien and even Japanese-Ryukyuan into the larger Austric hypothesis.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These peoples were assimilated linguistically and culturally by incoming Austronesian peoples in what is now modern-day Indonesia and Malaysia.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They propose that the distinctiveness of Kra-Dai (it is tonal and monosyllabic) was the result of linguistic restructuring due to contact with Hmong–Mien and Sinitic cultures.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Aside from linguistic evidence, Roger Blench has also noted cultural similarities between the two groups, like facial tattooing, tooth removal or ablation, teeth blackening, snake (or dragon) cults, and the multiple-tongued jaw harps shared by the indigenous Taiwanese and Kra-Dai-speakers.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, archaeological evidence for this is still sparse.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] This is believed to be similar to what happened to the Cham people, who were originally Austronesian settlers (likely from Borneo) to southern Vietnam around 2100–1900 BP and had languages similar to Malay.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Their languages underwent several restructuring events to syntax and phonology due to contact with the nearby tonal languages of Mainland Southeast Asia and Hainan.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Although the populations of the Malay peninsula, Sumatra, Java, and neighboring islands are Austronesian-speaking, they have significantly high admixture from Mainland Southeast Asian populations.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These areas were already populated (most probably by speakers of Austroasiatic languages) before they were reached by the Austronesian expansion, roughly 3,000 years ago.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Currently, only the indigenous Aslians still speak Austroasiatic languages.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, some of the languages in the region show signs of underlying Austroasiatic substrates.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] According to Juha Janhunen and Ann Kumar, Austronesians may have also settled parts of southern Japan, especially on the islands of Kyushu and Shikoku, and influenced or created the Japanese hierarchical society.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] It is suggested that Japanese tribes like the Hayato people, the Kumaso, and the Azumi were of Austronesian origin.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Until today, local traditions and festivals show similarities to Malayo-Polynesian culture.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Sino-Austronesian hypothesis, on the other hand, is a relatively new hypothesis by Laurent Sagart, first proposed in 1990.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] It argues for a north–south linguistic genetic relationship between Chinese and Austronesian.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] This is based on sound correspondences in basic vocabulary and morphological parallels.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Sagart places special significance in shared vocabulary on cereal crops, citing them as evidence of shared linguistic origin.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, this has largely been rejected by other linguists.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] This corresponded with the widespread introduction of rice cultivation to Proto-Sinitic speakers and conversely, millet cultivation to Pre-Austronesians.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] An Austronesian substratum in formerly Austronesian territories that have been Sinicized after the Iron Age Han expansion is also another explanation for the correspondences that do not require a genetic relationship.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The surviving Austronesian populations in Taiwan should rather be considered as the result of various Neolithic migration waves from the mainland and back-migration from the Philippines.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These incoming migrants almost certainly spoke languages related to Austronesian or pre-Austronesian, although their phonology and grammar would have been quite diverse.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Blench considers the Austronesians in Taiwan to have been a melting pot of immigrants from various parts of the coast of East China that had been migrating to Taiwan by 4000 BP.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Based on geography and cultural vocabulary, Blench believes that the Yuanshan people may have spoken Northeast Formosan languages.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Thus, Blench believes that there is in fact no "apical" ancestor of Austronesian in the sense that there was no true single Proto-Austronesian language that gave rise to present-day Austronesian languages.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Instead, multiple migrations of various pre-Austronesian peoples and languages from the Chinese mainland that were related but distinct came together to form what we now know as Austronesian in Taiwan.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Hence, Blench considers the single-migration model into Taiwan by pre-Austronesians to be inconsistent with both the archaeological and linguistic (lexical) evidence.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The **Austronesian expansion** (also called the "Out of Taiwan" model) is a large-scale migration of Austronesians from Taiwan, occurring around 3000 to 1500 BCE.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Population growth primarily fueled this migration.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] These first settlers settled in northern Luzon, in the archipelago of the Philippines, intermingling with the earlier Australo-Melanesian population who had inhabited the islands since about 23,000 years earlier.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Over the next thousand years, Austronesian peoples migrated southeast to the rest of the Philippines, and into the islands of the Celebes Sea and Borneo.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] From southwestern Borneo, Austronesians spread further west in a single migration event to both Sumatra and the coastal regions of southern Vietnam, becoming the ancestors of the speakers of the Malayic and Chamic branches of the Austronesian language family.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] A 2021 study, however, suggests an earlier divergence date between Cordilleran-related groups and populations from mainland East Asia and Taiwan at ~8,000 B.P., coinciding with the Cordilleran settlement of the Philippines.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Soon after reaching the Philippines, Austronesians colonized the Northern Mariana Islands by 1500 BCE or even earlier, becoming the first humans to reach Remote Oceania.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Chamorro migration was also unique in that it was the only Austronesian migration to the Pacific Islands to successfully retain rice cultivation.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Palau and Yap were settled by separate voyages by 1000 BCE.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Another important migration branch was by the Lapita culture, which rapidly spread into the islands off the coast of northern New Guinea and into the Solomon Islands and other parts of coastal New Guinea and Island Melanesia by 1200 BCE.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They reached the islands of Fiji, Samoa, and Tonga by around 900 to 800 BCE.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] This remained the furthest extent of the Austronesian expansion into Polynesia until around 700 CE, when there was another surge of island colonization.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] It reached the Cook Islands, Tahiti, and the Marquesas by 700 CE; Hawaii by 900 CE; Rapa Nui by 1000 CE; and New Zealand by 1200 CE.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] For a few centuries, the Polynesian islands were connected by bidirectional long-distance sailing, with the exception of Rapa Nui, which had limited further contact due to its isolated geographical location.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Island groups like the Pitcairns, the Kermadec Islands, and the Norfolk Islands were also formerly settled by Austronesians but later abandoned.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] There is also putative evidence, based in the spread of the sweet potato, that Austronesians may have reached South America from Polynesia, where they might have traded with the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] In the Indian Ocean, Austronesians in Maritime Southeast Asia established trade links with South Asia.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] They also established early long-distance contacts with Africa, possibly as early as before 500 BCE, based on archaeological evidence like banana phytoliths in Cameroon and Uganda and remains of Neolithic chicken bones in Zanzibar.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] By the end of the first millennium BCE, Austronesians were already sailing maritime trade routes linking the Han dynasty of China with the western Indian Ocean trade in India, the Roman Empire, and Africa.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] An Austronesian group, originally from the Makassar Strait region around Kalimantan and Sulawesi, eventually settled Madagascar, either directly from Southeast Asia or from preexisting mixed Austronesian-Bantu populations from East Africa.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Estimates for when this occurred vary, from the 5th to 7th centuries CE.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] It is likely that the Austronesians that settled Madagascar followed a coastal route through South Asia and East Africa, rather than directly across the Indian Ocean.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Genetic evidence suggests that some individuals of Austronesian descent reached Africa and the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] A competing hypothesis to the "Out of Taiwan" model is the "Out of Sundaland" hypothesis, favored by a minority of authors.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Notable proponents include William Meacham, Stephen Oppenheimer, and Wilhelm Solheim.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] For various reasons, they have proposed that the homelands of Austronesians were within Island Southeast Asia (ISEA), particularly in the Sundaland landmass drowned during the end of the Last Glacial Period by rising sea levels.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Proponents of these hypotheses point to the ancient origins of mtDNA in Southeast Asian populations, pre-dating the Austronesian expansion, as proof that Austronesians originated from within Island Southeast Asia.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] However, these have been repudiated by studies using whole genome sequencing, which have found that all ISEA populations had genes originating from aboriginal Taiwanese.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Contrary to the claim of a south-to-north migration in the "Out of Sundaland" hypothesis, the new whole genome analysis strongly confirms the north-to-south dispersal of the Austronesian peoples in the prevailing "Out of Taiwan" hypothesis.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Researchers have further pointed out that while humans have been living in Sundaland for at least 40,000 years, the Austronesian people were recent arrivals.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The results of the previous studies failed to take into account admixture with the more ancient but unrelated Negrito and Papuan populations.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] By the beginning of the first millennium CE, most of the Austronesian inhabitants in Maritime Southeast Asia began trading with India and China.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The adoption of the Hindu statecraft model allowed the creation of Indianized kingdoms, such as Tarumanagara, Champa, Butuan, Langkasuka, Melayu, Srivijaya, Mataram, Majapahit, and Bali.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Between the 5th and the 15th century, Hinduism and Buddhism were established as the main religion in the region.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Muslim traders from the Arabian Peninsula were thought to have brought Islam by the 10th century.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] This was established as the dominant religion in the Malay archipelago by the 16th century.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Austronesian inhabitants of Near Oceania and Remote Oceania were unaffected by this cultural trade and retained their indigenous culture in the Pacific region.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Kingdom of Larantuka in Flores, East Nusa Tenggara, was the only Christian (Roman Catholic) indigenous kingdom in Indonesia and in Southeast Asia, with its first king named Lorenzo.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] Meanwhile, the British, Germans, French, Americans, and Japanese began establishing spheres of influence within the Pacific islands during the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The Japanese later invaded most of Southeast Asia and some parts of the Pacific during World War II.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p01] The latter half of the 20th century initiated independence of modern-day Indonesia, Malaysia, East Timor, and many of the Pacific island nations, as well as the re-independence of the Philippines.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] The native culture of Austronesia varies from region to region.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] The early Austronesian peoples considered the sea as the basic feature of their life.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] Following their diaspora to Southeast Asia and Oceania, they migrated by boat to other islands.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] Boats of different sizes and shapes have been found in every Austronesian culture, from Madagascar, Maritime Southeast Asia, to Polynesia, and have different names.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] In Southeast Asia, head-hunting was restricted to the highlands as a result of warfare.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] Mummification is only found among the highland Austronesian Filipinos and in some Indonesian groups in Celebes and Borneo.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] Seagoing catamaran and outrigger ship technologies were the most important innovations of the Austronesian peoples.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] They were the first humans with vessels capable of crossing vast distances of water.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] The crossing from the Philippines to the Mariana Islands at around 1500 BCE, a distance of more than 2,500 km (1,600 mi), is likely the world's first and longest ocean crossing of that time.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] These maritime technologies enabled them to colonize the Indo-Pacific in prehistoric times.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] Austronesian groups continue to be the primary users of outrigger canoes today.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] Early researchers like Heine-Geldern (1932) and Hornell (1943) once believed that catamarans evolved from outrigger canoes, but modern authors specializing in Austronesian cultures, like Doran (1981) and Mahdi (1988), now believe it to be the opposite.
[src:chuuk-state/austronesian-peoples-p02] Two canoes bound together developed directly from minimal raft technologies of two logs tied together.
